    <h1>Authorization in Web Applications</h1>
    <p><strong>Authorization</strong> is the process of determining what a user is allowed to do. While authentication asks <em>"Who are you?"</em>, authorization asks <em>"What can you access?"</em></p>

    <h2>Why Authorization is Important</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Ensures only allowed users can access certain pages or features.</li>
        <li>Protects sensitive data from unauthorized users.</li>
        <li>Helps implement roles and permissions in your app.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example: Role-Based Authorization in ASP.NET Core</h2>
    <p>In ASP.NET Core, you can use roles to authorize users. For example:</p>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Authorize Admin Users Only</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;

[Authorize(Roles = "Admin")]
public class AdminController : Controller
{
    public IActionResult Dashboard()
    {
        return View();
    }
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>How It Works</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>The `[Authorize]` attribute checks if the user is logged in.</li>
        <li>The `Roles` parameter ensures only users with the specified role can access the controller or action.</li>
        <li>If a user does not meet the requirements, they are redirected to the login page or an "Access Denied" page.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Exercise</h2>
    <p>Practice role-based authorization:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Create two roles: `Admin` and `User`.</li>
        <li>Protect an "Admin Dashboard" page so only users with the `Admin` role can access it.</li>
        <li>Protect a "Profile" page so all logged-in users can access it.</li>
        <li>Test logging in with different users and observe which pages they can access.</li>
    </ul>

